---
import VizPlaceholder from '../../VizPlaceholder.astro';
---

<section
  id="answer"
  class="border-y border-neutral-900 bg-neutral-900/40 px-6 py-24 md:py-32"
>
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-6xl">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
      <h2
        class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-50 sm:text-5xl"
      >
        The answer: meta-harnesses
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-8 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-300">
        You have seen this move before. React gave you the core, and you chose
        the router, the data-fetching library, the component library, and
        stitched them together yourself. It worked, and it did not transfer:
        every team rebuilt the same setup differently. Then Next.js and
        TanStack Start packaged the proven choices into one box, and setting up
        a serious app stopped being someone's personal side quest.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-300">
        A meta-harness makes the same move around your harness. It fills the
        gaps you just saw with proven solutions instead of personal glue: it
        understands repositories and how they relate, provisions and
        coordinates agents across them, and turns sessions into shared
        memory. <strong class="font-semibold text-neutral-50"
          >You get more productive, your agent gets more capable, and with
          capability comes autonomy.</strong
        >
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mx-auto mt-14 max-w-5xl">
      <VizPlaceholder
        label="MetaHarnessLayers island: LLM core, harness ring, meta-harness ring closing the gaps"
        ratio="aspect-[16/10]"
      />
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
